steps.description:
Before gathering your supplies, you’ll need to have a good idea of the amount of room you have for your bedroom teepee. Measure the height of the room first, as you’ll need to use tall, ascending support poles while ensuring that the poles that will fit properly in the room. The support poles should fit in proportion to the room but not overpower it either––it's suggested that you leave some space between the top of the poles and the ceiling, to avoid a sense of it being too large. Determine how much fabric you’ll need. You will be wrapping the strategically placed support poles in a circular fashion and then wrapping the fabric around, starting from the top. Once you have a good idea as to how large you want your teepee, determine how much fabric you’ll need based on that size. For best results, overestimate the amount of fabric––you can always reduce the size if you have too much. When choosing fabric, consider whether you want it to be opaque or translucent, light or heavy, depending on the atmosphere you want to create and how much pressure the fabric will place on the poles. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ab/2163433-2-1-1.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-2-1-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ab/2163433-2-1-1.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-2-1-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Decide how many support poles you’ll need. This is based on the size of your room and/or bed. Larger rooms may require eight poles or more, whereas for a smaller bed (such as a toddler bed) you may only need three. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/20/2163433-2-2-1.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-2-2-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/20/2163433-2-2-1.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-2-2-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

The types of support poles depend mostly on your individual taste and overall room design, as well as using support poles that have adequate strength. Bring your measurements to the store so you can either purchase the support poles in the right size or have them cut to size. Some ideas for appropriate nook support poles include:
Rough branch-like poles. Simply go into nature and select actual tree branches. Of course, if you choose this method, they'll need to be thoroughly cleaned and varnished prior to use. Or you can see what the local craft store or a local craftsman offers. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/21/2163433-3-1-1.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-3-1-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/21/2163433-3-1-1.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-3-1-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Modern metal poles. Chrome or metal poles wrapped with a soft fabric flush may create a cool modern, yet comfortable appeal. You could even reuse tent poles or similar that are no longer useful for anything else––think recycle and make poles from anything useful about the house. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a5/2163433-3-2.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-3-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a5/2163433-3-2.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-3-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Wooden poles. The local hardware store can furnish you with a variety of wooden pole sizes and shapes. You can use them in their naked form or paint a color(s) that will complement the bedroom. Bamboo poles are a fairly typical kind of wooden pole available from garden stores and similar places. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3a/2163433-3-3.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-3-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3a/2163433-3-3.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-3-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Before assembling the teepee, there are a few important things to ensure that the support poles are in good shape:
Check the poles for dirt, blemishes, stains, insects, webs, etc. and do your best to clean them up. Some stains may simply end up being part of the charm of the final look, so don't worry too much if a stain won't budge––the most important thing is to ensure that the poles are hygienic for your bedroom space. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/64/2163433-4-1.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-4-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/64/2163433-4-1.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-4-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

If sanding is needed to avoid catching the fabric, do so now. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/2163433-4-2.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-4-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/2163433-4-2.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-4-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Place small rubber stoppers on the bottom of each support so it adheres to the floor. Even though the teepee will be secured from the top you won’t want the bottom to slip and bring the entire teepee down. The rubber stoppers should help to keep everything in place. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/19/2163433-4-3.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-4-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/19/2163433-4-3.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-4-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

You may need to ask a friend to help you create the teepee as it will require you to assemble the structure and secure it in place at the same time, something that's a bit tricky to do on your own. Ask your friend to stand on a ladder to receive the poles, then build the tepee nook as follows:
Hand one pole end to your friend from the opposite side of the tepee area. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1f\/2163433-5-1.jpg\/v4-459px-2163433-5-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1f\/2163433-5-1.jpg\/v4-759px-2163433-5-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Work your way around the area with the poles. Place the next pole on the opposite side of the area. Have your friend hold the top in place along with the other pole. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/0f\/2163433-5-2.jpg\/v4-459px-2163433-5-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/0f\/2163433-5-2.jpg\/v4-759px-2163433-5-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Tie the first two supports in place. In order to secure the poles, have your friend wind the string around the top of the poles. Leave a few inches (centimeters) above the tied string area. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/21\/2163433-5-3.jpg\/v4-459px-2163433-5-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/21\/2163433-5-3.jpg\/v4-759px-2163433-5-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Place the next few poles, working across opposite angles. Tie every two poles until you have all the poles in place, teepee style.

Using the fabric that enhances and complements your room, drape it over the tepee. Place the top portion of the fabric around the binding used for keeping the poles together––don't place the fabric over the top of the poles. The fabric should sit as high as possible while still allowing for the tops of the poles above the binding to peek out, as with a real teepee structure. For successful draping, try this method: Place fabric around the teepee from the middle of the sheet. Drape the fabric as though you are wrapping someone with a towel. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a9/2163433-7-1.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-7-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a9/2163433-7-1.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-7-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

For the best stability, consider using a staple gun or wire to attach the fabric to the top of the teepee structure, then add binding simply for decorative effect. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8f/2163433-7-2.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-7-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8f/2163433-7-2.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-7-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Allow the fabric to drape toward the front and hang down. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/2163433-7-3.jpg/v4-460px-2163433-7-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/2163433-7-3.jpg/v4-760px-2163433-7-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":387,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":639.039039039039,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Depending on the amount of fabric flapping over the entryway, you’ll need to fold back the “door” and secure using either a permanent or temporary method. If you want to keep the opening closed, you won’t need to secure the opening. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a4/2163433-8-1.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-8-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a4/2163433-8-1.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-8-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

If you want to keep a flap opened, there are several ways you can secure the door. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f1/2163433-8-2.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-8-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f1/2163433-8-2.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-8-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Create a door that can be opened and closed. One way to allow for the door to remain open but also be closed is to either use double stick Velcro tape or you can add a button and button hole to secure the door. Map out the place for which area of the fabric you want opened and where you’d like to be placed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d0/2163433-7-3-1.jpg/v4-460px-2163433-7-3-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d0/2163433-7-3-1.jpg/v4-760px-2163433-7-3-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":387,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":639.039039039039,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Design a door that can be permanently kept open. If you want to keep the door open permanently, you can simply sew the flap to the side of the teepee using a thread that is the same color of the fabric. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/14/2163433-8-4.jpg/v4-459px-2163433-8-4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/14/2163433-8-4.jpg/v4-759px-2163433-8-4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}
